Getting to Know Evalink Talos
What is Evalink Talos?
Evalink Talos is an online platform. You use it to manage security alarms. It's a software service that you access over
the internet.
The platform is built to be very reliable. It uses Amazon Web Services (AWS) with servers in America, Europe, and Asia.
These servers are in different "availability zones," which means if one area has a problem, the others can keep the
system running.
Talos is made up of many small, independent parts called "microservices." Each feature, like how sites are handled, or
how alarms are processed, is its own microservice. These parts talk to each other but can work on their own. This
design helps keep the platform highly available. If one small part has an issue, the rest of the system should operate
normally. This setup also makes it easier for the Evalink team to update the system, add new features, or fix problems
quickly and remotely.
When there's an update, especially a bigger one that changes how things look or work, the platform might ask you to
reload the page. Once you reload, the new updates are applied automatically.
How to See What's New
If you want to check for the latest releases and see what has changed in Talos:
1. Click on your Profile icon. This is usually in the top right corner of the screen.
2. In the menu that opens, look for an option called "What's new". Clicking this will show you information about
recent updates.
The Main Dashboard
When you first log into Talos, you'll usually see a dashboard. This page gives you a quick overview of important
information. You might see things like:
A summary of incoming alarms.
A list of alarms that are assigned to you or your team.
Other key numbers, charts, or integration statuses.
The main dashboard often shows how many alarms are coming in and if any are specifically assigned to you or your
team.
Understanding "Sites" in
Talos
In Talos, a "site" is basically anything that can create an alarm that you need to monitor. It's a flexible term.
A site could be a physical building, like an office, a factory, or a store.
It could be a specific area within a building, like one floor.
It could even be a personal panic button that someone carries.
If it can send an alarm signal, and you need to keep track of it, Talos calls it a site.
Site Status: Active vs. Inactive
Sites in Talos can have different statuses, which affect how they work and how they are billed.
Inactive Site:
If a site is "inactive," Talos will not accept any new alarms from it. You won't see any new alarms for this
site.
Importantly, you are usually not charged for sites that are marked as inactive.
Active Site:
An "active" site is fully operational. It can send alarms, those alarms will be processed, and the site counts
towards your billing.
Good Practice for Adding New Sites:
Let's say you know you're going to connect 100 new customer locations next week. A good approach is to create these
100 sites in Talos this week but set them all as inactive. You can get them all set up in the system, but you won't be
charged for them while you're waiting for the actual migration or connection. Then, when you're ready to bring them
online, you simply switch their status to "active."
Using "Test Mode" for Sites
Sometimes, you'll need to put a site into "test mode." This is useful if you know there's going to be a lot of activity that
isn't real (like technicians working on sensors) or if you're testing new configurations.
When a site is in test mode, you can configure Talos to: 
Treat certain types of alarms from that site as "test alarms." These are often ignored for normal operator
queues or logged differently.
Still allow other critical alarm types from that same site to come through as real, actionable alarms.
Example of Test Mode:
Imagine a factory is replacing all its motion sensors over a weekend. You expect many motion detection alarms during
this work, and they aren't real intrusions. However, the factory's fire alarm system must remain fully operational.
You can put the factory site into a specific test mode where Talos is told: "For this weekend, ignore all motion detection
alarms from the factory because of the sensor upgrade. But, if any fire alarms come in, treat those as urgent and real."
This way, operators aren't distracted by the test motion signals but will still respond immediately to a genuine fire alert.
Exploring Sites and Connections
The "Sites" Page: Your Customer List
After the main dashboard and the alarms page, the "Sites" page is another important area.
This page shows you a list of all your customer sites.
You can filter this list to see sites that are "active," "inactive," or in "test mode."
You can also use search and other filters (like "installer company," if you use that feature) to find specific sites
quickly.
The table showing your sites can often be customized. You can usually click on an icon (often three dots or a settings
gear) to change which columns are visible, like adding specific custom fields or changing the order of information. This
lets operators or administrators set up a view that works best for them.
Virtual Devices: Understanding Connections
Within the "Sites" page, there's often a tab or section called "Virtual Devices."
This area lists all the "receivers" or connections for all your customers. These aren't physical hardware boxes in
your office; they are virtual connection points in the Talos cloud.
You'll see an overview of these connections, including their current status (e.g., connected, disconnected).
Status is often shown with icons: 
Green usually means connected and healthy.
Red might indicate a disconnected device.
You can filter this list to quickly see, for example, all disconnected devices that might need attention.
When you click on a specific virtual device (a specific connection), you can see more details, like the receiver account
number. If you click on an icon next to the device entry, it will often take you directly to the site or customer associated
with that connection.
Understanding Connection Paths (Single Path vs. Dual Path)
When looking at a virtual device's details, you might see information about its connection paths:
Single Path (SP): The device communicates through one channel only (e.g., only Ethernet). If that channel is
connected, the device is considered connected.
Dual Path (DP): The device has two communication channels (e.g., Ethernet and a mobile/cellular backup). For
the device to be considered fully connected, both paths might need to be active, or it might show the status of
each path individually.
For example, a device might show:
Ethernet: Connected (Green)
Mobile: Connected (Green)
Overall Device Status: Connected (Green)
If one path drops (e.g., Ethernet goes down, but Mobile is still up), the status would change, alerting you to a potential
issue while the backup path keeps it online.
You can usually search this virtual device list by the account number if you need to find a specific connection quickly.
Organizing Sites: Levels of Grouping
While a "site" is the basic level for an alarm-generating entity, Talos allows you to group sites for better organization,
reporting, and for applying workflows to multiple sites at once.
Sites: The lowest, most basic level – your individual customer locations.
Site Groups: You can group multiple sites together. For example, if a customer is a supermarket chain, a site
group could represent all their stores in a specific region (e.g., "North Holland Stores").
Organizational Units: This is often a higher level of grouping. The supermarket chain itself could be an
"Organizational Unit." Site groups (regions) would then fall under this main organizational unit.
This grouping is flexible and not mandatory. However, it helps a lot when you need to:
Get an overview of all connections in a specific region.
Generate reports for a particular customer or group of sites.
Apply certain scenarios or workflows to all sites within a group (e.g., a holiday schedule for all stores in a
particular city).
Service Companies: A Special Type of Group
There's also a concept called "Service Companies."
A Service Company is an independent group you can define, like a specific electrician, a guard service, or a
maintenance company.
You can then link this Service Company to multiple different sites, even if those sites belong to different
customers.
Example: The same electrician might be responsible for five different customer sites in a particular area. You can
create a "Service Company" entry for this electrician and link them to all five sites.
Benefit: If Talos detects a technical issue (like a power outage reported by a site's alarm panel), a workflow could
be set up to automatically send a notification (like an SMS or email) to the linked Service Company (the
electrician) to go and check on that site.
Create a Site
Site Creation Options
Methods of Site Creation
There are two ways to create a site in evalink talos:
from scratch
from a template
Creating a site from a template is useful when you need to create multiple sites that share a common set of parameters
– for example, use the same types of integrations, have the same working hours, monitor the same set of site statuses,
forward alarms to a common monitoring station, etc.
All these settings can be applied to the site automatically during the site creation, with a possibility to edit them
afterwards.
Site Templates are configured on a global level under Company > Settings > Sites. Only Administrator and Manager have
the permissions to create and manage Site Templates.
Setting Site ID
When creating a site, there are the following options for specifying the Site ID (the name of the site):
typing the Site ID manually
This option is always available when creating a site from scratch.
When creating a site from a template, it is possible to manually enter the Site ID if the template:
provides the Site ID input Field
is not configured to create an auto-generated Side ID (see below)
setting an auto-generated Site ID
You can have evalink talos generate the Site ID as a random-looking numeric value.
The Site ID value is generated based on a sequence – a user-defined configuration that specifies the start value of
the number (for example, 51500000) and the optional constant prefix and suffix that are added to the number (for
example, VdS- or -ArmStatus).
For each new created site, the last assigned value from the sequence is incremented by 1. For example, after a site
with Site ID 51500000 is created, other sites that are created using the sequence will have Site
IDs 51500001, 51500002, etc.
Auto-generated Site IDs can be applied both to the sites created from scratch and to the sites created from a
template.
Site ID sequences are configured on a global level under Company > Settings > Sites. Same as with site templates,
sequences can be created and managed by Administrator and Manager only.
Create a Site from Scratch
To create a site from scratch:
1. On the Sites page, click the Create Site button
2. In the dialog that opens
a. Select the Basic option
Basic is the default option if no templates have been configured for the Company yet. If at least one Site Template
is 
configured, the default option is From Template.
b. In the Site ID field, type the site ID (the name of the site)
The site name must be unique within the Company and can contain letters, digits, special symbols and emoji.
To generate a Site ID automatically, click the Sequence button in the Site ID field and select the desired sequence from
the list. The generated Site ID is populated into the field.
info
To be able to auto-generate a Site ID, you need to have at least one sequence configured under Company > Settings > Sites.
c. If you want the site to be in Active status after creation, leave the Activate Site checkbox selected. Otherwise,
clear the     checkbox
d. Click Create
Create a Site from Template
tip
Note that, if the Site ID field is present on the form (always mandatory), and the Site Template includes Site ID auto-
generation (see section Setting Site ID), the auto-generated Site ID takes precedence over the manually entered one.
During the site creation, there is no way to find out if Site ID auto-generation is included in the Site Template, but it is
possible to edit the Site ID on the site Settings page afterwards.
Edit the Site Settings
To edit the site settings:
1. Go to the Sites page, select the site from the list
2. On the Overview page that opens, scroll down to the middle of the page and click Settings
3. On the Settings subpage that opens, enter or edit the following information:
In the Site pane, specify the Site ID and select a Site Group for the site
In the Address pane, specify the company details for the site
In the Time Zone pane, select the Time Zone for the site
The Your time zone field displays your current time zone. Click the name of your time zone to set it as the site
time zone. When your time zone is set as the site time zone, the Your time zone field is not displayed.
In the Custom Fields pane, specify the values for custom fields, or click Configure to setup a new custom field
Custom Fields
A custom field is a variable that stores information related to a site and used in workflows. Custom fields can also be
created for site groups.
For example, for a company that monitors vehicles, you can create a License plate custom field. Then, you can specify a
License plate number for each monitored vehicle and use it in your workflows.
Custom Fields are created on a global level. After a custom field is created, it appears on the Settings page of all sites (or
site groups) created under the Company account.
To configure a custom field:
1. Go to the Company > Settings > Sites
You can go to this page directly from the Settings page of a particular site (or site group) by clicking on
the Configure         shortcut in the Custom Fields area of the page.
2. On the Company > Settings > Sites page, click Add Custom Field
3. In the dialog that opens, specify:
Name – the custom field ID to be used by evalink talos internally
The name can contain only letters and numbers. It is recommended to follow the best practices used for
programming language variables, such as lowerCamelCase: testRecord, invoiceNumber, etc.
Type – determines what type of data is stored in the field
You can the select one of the following:
Text – the value can contain any character, including letters, digits, and keyboard symbols
Number – the value can contain whole numbers – positive, negative, or zero
Select One – one value from the list can be selected
Select Multiple – multiple values from the list can be selected
    When you select an enumerated type (Select One or Select Multiple), an Option field appears at the bottom of the
dialog.     To add more options to the list, click the Add Option button.
Display – the custom field name to be displayed in evalink talos UI
Scope – determines if the custom field value is set for sites only or for site groups only
Sites (the default option)
the custom field is offered for filling on the Settings page of each site
the value of the custom field (if set) is displayed on the Overview page of the site
Site Groups
the custom field is offered for filling on the Settings page of each site group
the value of the custom field (if set) is displayed on the Overview page of each site that is included
into the group and on the Overview page of the site group itself
(Optional) Validation pattern – an expression for user input validation
The custom field value must match the validation pattern value. Validation pattern follows regular expressions
syntax. For example, the ^[0-9]*$ expression allows entering only numbers in a custom field.
Validation patterns can only be configured for Text and Number types of custom fields.
(Optional) select the Public checkbox to include custom field information in PDF and email reports
(Optional) select the Operator checkbox to display the custom field to the Operator
Operator will see custom fields for a site on the operator Workflow page when processing an alarm
(Optional) select the Hidden checkbox to hide the custom field value from the Overview pages of the concerned
sites or site groups
This option is useful for storing sensitive information.
4. Click Submit
By default, custom fields are displayed on the site / site group Settings and Overview pages in the order in which they
were added. To reorder custom fields, go to Company > Settings > Sites page and move the custom fields as desired by
clicking on ↑ and ↓ (arrow) buttons to the right of each custom field.
info
Name and Type of an existing custom field cannot be edited.
warning
To be able to delete a custom field on the Company > Settings > Sites page, first erase all the custom field values specified
for all sites / site groups.
Site Code Words
Code word for a site is used for the call communication with a person belonging to the site when that person is not
recorded as a site contact in evalink talos.
Site code words are used for IN-CALL alarms, to allow many people to act as contacts on behalf of a site.
For example, for a site with many employees, such as a department store, you can configure one code word on a site
level and share it with employees. This way you don’t need to add an excessive number of site contacts and create a
code word for each contact.
You can have multiple code words for a site and assign them to different contact groups. Use 'Master' and 'General'
name templates, or create a code word with an arbitrary name. For example, you can set a 'Master' code word for the site
managers, and a 'General' code word for employees with less permissions.
When Operator receives a call from a person on behalf of a site, the phone number may be known or unknow to evalink
talos.
If the phone number is registered in evalink talos, the site details including the code word, are displayed in the
incoming call dialog box
If the phone number is not registered in evalink talos, Operator uses a Codeword Search to find the relevant site
info
When Operator verifies the site and triggers an IN-CALL alarm, the alarm and associated workflow are automatically
assigned to Operator.
Delete a Site
Before attempting to delete a site, make sure that none of enabled site receivers are in Connected status through ethernet
or mobile.
The figure below shows an example of a connected receiver, configured for a site:
To delete a site:
1. On the Sites page, click on the site record in the list
2. On the Overview page of the site that opens, scroll to the middle of the page and click the Settings button
3. Scroll to the bottom of the Settings subpage and click the Delete button
4. Enter the confirmation code and click Delete
warning
After a site is deleted, the contacts, workflows, and schedules configured for it are also deleted permanently. The records
originating from the site disappear from the Events and Event Log pages.
Working with Alarms and Workflows
The Alarms Page: Your Main Hub for Events
When alarms come into Talos, the "Alarms" page is where operators will typically see and manage them. Think of it as
the central buffer for incoming events that need attention.
Layout:
Left Side (Alarm Buffer): This area lists new alarms that have arrived and haven't been picked up or
assigned to an operator yet.
Right Side (Workflows/Operator View): This area usually shows information about "workflows" (we'll talk
more about these in a moment) and which operators are active or working on specific alarms.
Understanding the Workflow Columns
On the right side of the Alarms page, you'll see columns, often labeled with operator names or group names (like
"NXGEN ADMIN," "NXGEN SUPPORT," "Operatore SVAT" in your examples).
These columns show which alarms are currently assigned to or being worked on by specific users or teams.
You can see if users are "Online" or "Offline."
If a user has alarms assigned, they'll appear under their name. If they have no active alarms, it might say "doesn't
have any alarms assigned" or show a "Clear" status.
Filtering Alarms and Operator Views
At the top of the workflow/operator view section, there are usually filters. These let you change what you see:
"Assigned to anyone" (Default): Shows all unassigned alarms in the buffer and all assigned alarms under the
respective operators.
"Assigned to active users": Filters to show only alarms assigned to operators currently logged in and active.
"Assigned to you": Shows only alarms assigned directly to you.
Specific Users/Groups: You can often select specific users (like "Assigned to NXGEN ADMIN") to see only their
workload. This is helpful for supervisors or team leads.
As operators log in or start working on alarms, their status and assigned alarms will update in these columns.
Useful Buttons on the Alarms Page
At the top of the Alarms page (often above the alarm buffer), there are some helpful buttons:
1. Trigger Alarm (Bell Icon):
This button allows administrators or testers to manually simulate an alarm. It's very useful for testing how
different alarm types are processed by your workflows and how the system behaves.
When you click it, you can typically:
Select a Site to trigger the alarm for.
Choose an Alarm Definition or Alarm Code (e.g., "100-Medical," "102-Fail to Report In," "110-
Fire").
Specify if it's an "Alarm/Restore," a "Technical" alarm, or just a "Test Message."
This helps you see how a specific alarm would go through your configured scenarios without waiting for a
real event.
2. Incoming Call (Phone Icon):
This feature is helpful when an operator receives a phone call related to a site or alarm, perhaps on a
separate desk phone.
Clicking this button tells Talos "I'm handling an incoming call." You can then search for the site or contact
using information the caller provides, like a site name, a contact name, or a "codeword."
A codeword is a unique number or phrase assigned to a person or site. If a caller provides a codeword,
the operator can quickly search for it in Talos to identify who is calling and which site they are referring to.
What are Workflows?
Workflows are a core part of how Talos manages alarms.
A workflow is a set of predefined steps or a scenario that guides how a specific type of alarm should be handled.
Workflows ensure that alarms are processed consistently and that operators follow the correct procedures.
They can be manual (guiding an operator step-by-step) or automated (where the system performs actions
without human interaction).
When an alarm comes into the buffer on the left, it usually gets picked up by a workflow. The workflow then dictates
what happens next – whether it's assigned to an operator, if automated calls are made, if information is logged, etc.
More below:
A workflow is a sequence of actions that are performed by evalink talos to process an alarm.
info
An alarm is always triggered for a certain site. Therefore, a workflow, though it can be created on different levels (site, site
group, or global), is always executed for a particular site.
A workflow allows to implement a complete specialized end-to-end procedure for handling each type of alarm.
A workflow may include several conditional branches. Each branch can contain a separate action or a sequence of
actions. For example, when a burglary alarm comes in, a workflow can be configured to verify the alarm by contacting a
responsible person and, depending on the result:
if the alarm is real, notify an intervention team
if the alarm is a false positive, close the workflow
A workflow can also be configured to execute several branches (sequences of actions) in parallel.
The figure below shows a workflow opened in the workflow editor. The editor opens when you click on the workflow on
the Workflows page. The workflow editor view (see below) is the same for site, site group, and global workflows.
The figure below shows the same workflow in the workflow processing view – a view that is available to the operator
while processing the workflow:
The actions highlighted in bold blue are the actions that were actually performed when the workflow followed the
corresponding conditional branch.
tip
As you can see from the two examples, when the workflow is executed, the Guards (Role) contact set in the workflow
editor resolves to a particular site contact assigned with the Guards role (John Doe). For more details on how roles are
used in workflows, see section Workflow Types > Site, Site Group, and Global Workflows > Use of Roles in Site Group and
Global Workflows.
Only Administrator and Manager can create, edit or delete workflows.
Workflow Structure
A workflow consists of the following principal blocks:
incoming conditions
settings
steps
Workflow Incoming Conditions
An alarm that is received for a site can be assigned to a certain workflow automatically, based on a set of incoming
conditions that are configured for the workflow by Administrator or Manager. Incoming conditions may include, for
example, an alarm code, the zone and / or partition, the alarm value (Alarm or Restore), a regular expression in the
payload, etc., or any combination of such parameters.
The incoming conditions for a workflow are set in the Incoming Alarm step, see the figure below:
An alarm that satisfies the incoming conditions of the workflow above:
arrives during the hours of the Business Hours schedule
AND
has a value Alarm (alarms with Restore value do not trigger the current workflow)
AND either
is triggered from zone 5 – Server room or from zone 6 – Server room 2
OR
has one of these alarm codes: 350, 351, or 352
If one of the above condition combinations is fulfilled, an alarm is considered a match and triggers the workflow.
Keeping Track: Event Logs, Alarms, and Jobs
Event Logs: Seeing What's Happening
Talos keeps a detailed record of activities related to your sites and customers. This is found in the "Event Logs."
You can see a history of events like:
Sites being armed or disarmed.
Workflows being executed.
Alarms arriving.
Rule violations (e.g., a site not armed on schedule).
Changes in site status (e.g., from inactive to active).
You can filter these logs by a date range (e.g., the last week, or a custom period). You can also filter by specific event
types, alarm codes, or zones to narrow down your search. This is very useful for investigating past incidents or
reviewing site activity.
Data Retention:
How long are these logs kept?
For trial accounts, it's typically 90 days.
For regular paid customers, it's usually one and a half years.
If different retention times are needed, this can sometimes be adjusted by discussing with Evalink.
Events Page: Focusing on Alarms
The "Events" page gives you a more focused view, specifically on the alarms themselves.
You'll see a list of alarms, which site they came from, and details about the alarm type.
You can see if an alarm was a "test message," a "technical alarm," or a standard alarm/restore signal.
Understanding Alarm Details
When you click on any alarm in the Events list, you get more detailed information:
Alarm Timestamps:
You'll see when the alarm arrived in the Talos system.
You'll also see a "Transmission time" (e.g., 5ms). This is how long Talos took to process the alarm and get
it ready to show you, from the moment the system first received it. This is usually very quick.
Alarm Headers & Information:
Alarms come with extra pieces of information called "headers." Some are standard, and some can be
added by your workflows or system settings.
Type of Event: Indicates if it's a regular alarm, a technical alarm (e.g., device malfunction), or a restore
signal (e.g., burglary alarm restored).
Payload: For technical users, the "payload" shows the raw data exactly as it was sent by the device. This
can be useful for troubleshooting complex issues with how a device is sending signals.
Receiver Information: Shows which virtual receiver in Talos received the alarm and details about the
source device (like its DCO9 account number).
Integrity Score: Talos has an internal "integrity" score for alarms. If a site constantly sends the same
alarm over and over, this score might go down, suggesting the signal might be less reliable or potentially a
nuisance. A score of 1 is highest, 0 is lowest.
Channel: This is an advanced feature that can be used to route alarms to specific operators or groups
based on criteria like language (e.g., "English speaking customer alarms go to English speaking
operators") or alarm type (e.g., "Fire alarms go to the fire specialist team").
Dispatch Account: If you're forwarding alarms from Talos to another alarm receiving system (common
during migrations or for specific clients), this header shows which account was used for that dispatch.
X-Channel, X-IP, X-Receiver: These provide more technical details about the communication path the
alarm took to get into Talos.
X-Tags: Tags are like custom labels you can put on sites (e.g., "English Speaker," "VIP Customer," "Has
Video"). If an alarm comes from a tagged site, those tags will appear in the alarm headers, giving
operators quick context.
Real ID: A unique identification number for that specific alarm event within Talos. You'll also see this ID in
the URL when you open the alarm.
Category: Alarms are grouped into categories (e.g., "CONNECTION," "BURGLARY," "FIRE"). This helps
with organizing and reporting.
Alarm Definitions and Categories
Talos needs to understand the different alarm codes sent by various devices.
Alarm Definitions: The system has predefined lists of alarm codes (like from the "Contact ID Standard" or "SIA
Standard"). For example, code "130" in Contact ID usually means a burglary alarm.
You can find these definitions in Company Settings > Alarms > Alarm Definitions.
You can search for specific codes to see what they mean.
These definitions can often be viewed in a simple list or in a technical JSON format if you need to make
many changes.
Alarm Categories: As mentioned, alarms are grouped into categories. You can see and sometimes customize
these categories in Company Settings > Alarms > Alarm Categories. You can also adjust the default "Severity"
level for different categories if needed.
Jobs: Tracking Tasks
Talos includes a "Jobs" feature, which is like a simple task or ticket management system.
You can create jobs that are linked to specific sites.
You can assign a job to a person, set a due date, add comments, and track its status (e.g., "Open").
Example: If a virtual receiver for a site is having connection issues, you could create a job assigned to a
technical operator: "Check mobile connection for Site XYZ's panel. Due by [Date]."
You can define different "Job Types" in Company Settings > Jobs > Job Types (e.g., "Technical Maintenance,"
"Alarm Follow-up," "Transmitter Trouble").
Analytics, Calls, and Company Settings
Analytics Page: A Quick Status Overview
The "Analytics" page in Talos gives you a quick overview of the status of your sites.
You can see things like: 
Arm Status: How many sites are armed or disarmed.
Connection Status: The primary and secondary connection health for your sites.
The page often uses circular charts or graphs to show these statuses at a glance.
You can usually filter this view by specific site groups, tags, or individual sites to get a more focused look.
There's often a way to switch between a "Live" view of current statuses and a "Stats" view that might show trends
over time.
This page is good for a quick check on the overall health and operational status of your monitored sites.
Note on Advanced Analytics:
Sometimes, there's an "Open Analytics" button on the main dashboard. This can lead to a more advanced analytics
feature (often using a tool like Grafana) which might be a separate subscription. This advanced section can show
detailed operator performance, alarm trends, workflow activity, and more. The basic "Analytics" page we just talked
about is for general status an overview and is usually available to all customers.
Talos Calls: Managing Phone Interactions
The "Talos Calls" section is where you manage and review phone calls made or received through the system,
especially if you're using an integrated VoIP service like Twilio.
You can see a list of all calls, both incoming and outgoing.
Details typically include: 
The phone number involved.
Date and time of the call.
The site related to the call.
The operator who handled the call.
Any notes added.
If call recording is enabled, you can often listen to recordings directly from this page.
There might be options to see forwarded calls or take other actions.
This page is useful for tracking communications, reviewing operator interactions, and quality assurance.
Company Menu: Settings and Overviews
The "Company" menu is a central place for administrators to manage tenant-wide settings, users, integrations, and
more. Let's look at some key parts.
1. Users & Roles: Managing Access
Users: This section lists everyone who has access to your Talos platform. You can see their email, status (e.g.,
invited, active), and the roles assigned to them.
You can invite new users by entering their email and assigning them a "User Type."
User Types & Roles:
Talos has default user types (like Company Admin, Manager, Operator, Operator Minimal) that define a
general level of permission.
You can also create custom Roles. A role is a set of specific permissions that dictate what a user can see
and do.
For example, an "Operator" role might be able to manage alarms but not change company settings. A
"Super Operator" role could be an operator with some extra permissions, like deleting alarms or doing
mass alarm actions.
When you create or edit a role, you'll see a long list of permissions you can check or uncheck (e.g.,
"Alarm:Create," "Alarm:Delete," "Site:Update").
Workspaces: User types can also be linked to "Workspaces." Workspaces are a way to group sites (e.g.,
by language, region, or client type). You can then assign operators to a specific workspace so they only
see and manage alarms for those sites. This is useful if you have operators specializing in certain
languages or regions.
2. Company Profile:
In the Company section, you can edit basic company profile information, such as the company name, default
language for the interface, contact phone number, email, and upload a company logo (which might appear on
reports or the UI).
3. Alarm Settings: Customizing Alarm Handling
This is an important area within Company > Settings > Alarms.
Escalation of Stale Alarms: You can set up rules to automatically notify someone (e.g., a manager via email or
SMS) if an alarm sits in the queue for too long (e.g., 5 minutes) without an operator acting on it. This helps
ensure critical alarms don't get missed, especially during busy times or if an operator is unavailable. You can filter
which alarms trigger this escalation (e.g., only "real" non-test alarms, or only specific types like "Fire").
Alarm Categories & Severity:
We talked about alarm categories before (Access Control, Burglary, Bypass, Call, Comment, etc.). Here
you can review them.
You can also adjust the default Severity for alarms within these categories. Severity is often a number
(e.g., 0-999), with higher numbers indicating higher importance. If your company considers burglary
alarms extremely critical, you could increase their default severity.
Alarm Sounds: You can customize the sounds Talos makes for new alarms. You can upload different sound files
and even assign specific sounds to particular alarm types (e.g., a very distinct, urgent sound for a fire alarm, and
a different sound for a technical alert). If no custom sound is set for an alarm type, it will use a default sound.
More Company Settings: Workflows, Contacts, Schedules, and Connections
Continuing from the last section, let's explore more settings under the "Company" menu. These settings help you
customize how Talos operates for your entire organization or specific parts of it.
1. Workflow Settings: Fine-Tuning Alarm Handling
Under Company > Settings > Workflows, you'll find options to adjust how workflows behave.
Auto-Parking Workflows:
What it is: If an operator starts working on an alarm (which starts a workflow) but then becomes inactive
(e.g., steps away, gets busy with something else), Talos can automatically "park" that workflow.
Why it's useful: Parking a workflow takes it away from the inactive operator and puts it back into the
general queue (the alarm buffer). This allows another available operator to pick it up and continue working
on it, so alarms don't get stuck.
How it works: You can enable "Auto park workflow due to operator inactivity." Then you set a time (e.g.,
300 seconds, which is 5 minutes). If the operator is inactive on that workflow for 5 minutes, they might get
a warning for the last 30 seconds, and then the workflow is automatically parked.
Grouping Alarms in Manual Workflows:
This setting decides how new alarms from the same site are handled if an operator is already working on
an active workflow for that site.
Don't group (Default for some setups): Every new alarm starts a brand new workflow. This means
multiple operators could be working on different alarms from the same site at the same time.
Group alarms of the same site (Often the default): If an operator is working on an alarm from Site A,
and another alarm (any type) comes in from Site A, the new alarm gets added to the existing, active
workflow. Only one operator handles all current alarms for that site.
Group alarms by condition: This is a bit more specific. For example, you could set it to group new
burglary alarms with an existing burglary workflow, but if a fire alarm comes in from the same site, the fire
alarm would start its own separate workflow.
It's usually best to start with the default setting (often "Group alarms of the same site") and adjust later if
your operational needs are different.
2. Contacts & Contact Roles: Knowing Who to Call
Under Company > Settings > Contacts, you manage how contact information is used.
Contact Roles:
These are like labels or aliases for contacts. Examples could be "Maintenance," "Guard," "Keyholder,"
"Branch Manager."
You create these roles (e.g., "Maintenance," "Installer"). Then, when you add actual contact people to a
site, you can assign them one or more of these roles.
Why they're useful: In a workflow, instead of saying "Call John Smith," you can say "Call the contact with
the 'Maintenance' role for this site." Talos will then look up who has that role for the specific site involved in
the alarm and provide their details to the operator or even use it in an automated call. This makes
workflows more flexible, as the actual person might change, but the role stays the same.
Contact Relationships: This is just an extra note field you can add to a contact to describe their affiliation or
status. It doesn't directly change how the system operates but can be helpful for operator reference.
3. Status Roles & Schedule Roles: Adding Logic
Status Roles: These link to the site statuses we talked about (like "Armed," "Disconnected"). You can define
roles for these statuses. For example, you can have a "Connection Status" role with states like "Connected" or
"Disconnected."
Why they're useful: In workflows, you can then check the role of a status. For example, a workflow step
could be: "If the 'Arm Status' role for this site is currently 'Armed', then do X. If it's 'Disarmed', then do Y."
Schedule Roles: Schedules (which we'll cover next) can also have roles. For instance, you might create a
schedule named "Opening Hours." You can then assign this a "Schedule Role" of, say, "Business_Hours."
Why they're useful: Workflows can then check this role. A workflow might say: "If the current time falls
within a schedule that has the 'Business_Hours' role, then do X. If not, do Y."
4. Schedules & Special Days: Automating by Time
Schedules are a powerful way to automate actions based on time and day. These are usually managed within a site's
settings, but global schedule templates can be created under Company > Schedules.
Creating Schedules: You define entries for different days of the week and times. For example, "Opening Hours"
could be Monday-Friday, 9 AM to 5 PM.
Special Days: You can define global "Special Days," like public holidays (e.g., "King's Day," "New Year's Day").
You can set if these are recurring annually or are one-time. 
When you create a site's schedule, you can include these global special days. If a special day (like a
holiday) is included in a site's schedule, the site might follow a different pattern for that day (e.g., remain
"closed" or "armed" even if it's a weekday). This saves you from having to manually adjust every site's
schedule for common holidays.
5. Receivers & SLAs: Managing Connections
Under Company > Settings > Receivers, you manage settings related to how Talos communicates with alarm panels
or devices.
Virtual Device Types: You can define "Virtual Device Types." These allow you to assign a specific alarm
definition (like "Contact ID Standard" or "SIA Standard") to a type of receiver. For example, if you know all your
Ajax panels send alarms in a specific SIA format, you could create a "Standard Ajax Panel" virtual device type
and link it to the correct alarm definition. When you then set up a new Ajax connection for a site, you can assign it
this type.
SLAs (Service Level Agreements): This defines how often Talos "polls" or checks the connection with a
receiver/panel to ensure it's still online.
There are predefined SLAs (e.g., for dual path or single path connections, with different polling intervals).
You can also create custom SLAs if you need specific polling and reporting times for certain types of
connections. For example, you could define a custom SLA with a polling interval of 90 seconds and a
reporting time (how long to wait before flagging a connection issue) of 200 seconds.
6. Dispatcher: Forwarding Alarms
The Dispatcher setting (under Company > Settings) is used if you need to forward alarms received by your Talos
tenant to another monitoring station or alarm management system. This is often used during migrations from an
old system or if you subcontract monitoring to another company. You configure the connection details (IPs, ports,
protocols) of the external monitoring station here.
7. Table Configurations: Customizing Your Views
Under Company > Settings > Tables Configuration, you can customize the default columns and their order for
various list views in Talos, like the Event Logs, Events list, and Sites list. This allows you to tailor these views to
show the information most relevant to your operations.
8. Subscription Information:
The Company > Settings > Subscription page shows details about your Evalink Talos subscription, including
critical information like the data retention period for your logs and events (e.g., 90 days for trial, 1.5 years for
paid). It might also show your unique Company ID, which can be useful if you're working with the Talos API for
custom integrations.
Communication, Reporting, and Logging
1. Chat Feature
Talos includes a built-in chat feature for communication between users who are logged into the platform.
Accessing Chat: You'll usually find a chat icon or section in the main menu.
Direct Messages: You can search for a specific person who is online and send them a direct message. When
you send a message about a particular site, you can often link the site to the chat, so the other person knows
exactly which customer or location you're talking about.
Channels: You can create chat "channels" and choose who participates. This is useful for team communication.
For example:
You could have a channel for all operators. If an operator is working on a busy alarm and needs help, they
can quickly message the group.
You could have a separate channel for managers or administrators to discuss system changes or other
topics.
2. Reports: Getting Data Out
Talos has a reporting system to help you get information out of the platform, often in PDF format. These settings are
usually found under Company > Settings > Reports.
"Enable next generation reports": This toggle should generally always be kept ON to use the more advanced
and customizable reporting features.
PDF Templates: Talos uses templates to create PDF reports. You can define how a report looks and what
information it includes.
Categories of Templates:
WorkflowEventLog: This type of report shows the outcome of a completed workflow – what
happened step-by-step when an operator handled an alarm scenario.
AlarmListReport: This gives you a list of alarms, similar to what you see on the "Events" page.
SiteDocumentation: This could be a template to output all the key information about a specific site.
Global Usage/Default: You can set a default template to be used for each report category.
Customizing Templates: The templates are defined using a type of code (Angular-based). This allows for
a lot of flexibility in what's included and how it's laid out (e.g., company logos, specific data fields,
comments). If you need very custom reports, you might work with Evalink support or your technical team
to define these templates. Things like the size of your logo in the report can be changed directly in the
template code.
Extracting Reports: When you're viewing something like a completed workflow log, you'll often have an
option to "Export PDF" using one of your defined templates.
A Note on Report Size: If you try to generate a report for a very large amount of data (e.g., an alarm list for 100
sites over a month, with thousands of alarms), the resulting PDF could be hundreds of pages long and difficult to
manage. For very large data exports, using the advanced analytics features to export data as a CSV
(spreadsheet) file might be a better option.
Data Sources for Reports:
The reports pull information from various "data sources" within Talos (e.g., alarm lists, event logs, contact
lists, site details).
If you have very specific needs, it's sometimes possible to create custom SQL queries to pull unique
combinations of data from your Talos database to include in reports.
3. Predefined Text Blocks: Helping Operators Work Faster
This is a handy feature found under Company > Settings > Predefined Text Blocks.
Purpose: Administrators can create standard text snippets in advance. Operators can then quickly insert these
snippets when they are typing notes or comments, for example, when handling an alarm in a workflow.
Benefits:
Saves Time: Operators don't have to type the same common phrases repeatedly.
Reduces Mistakes: Ensures consistent and accurate wording for standard communications.
Multi-language: You can define the same text block in multiple languages (e.g., "Police dispatched" in
English, French, Dutch).
How it Works:
a. Admins create a text block (e.g., "Police dispatched to location. ETA 10 minutes.").
b. They define the "context" where this block should be available (e.g., in workflow comments, in call logs, in
reports).
c. When an operator is in a text field that matches that context, they can select the predefined block from a
menu instead of typing it all out.
4. Logs: Keeping an Eye on System Activity
Talos keeps several types of logs to track what's happening.
Log Notification Rules:
Found under Company > Settings > Logs > Log Notification Rules.
You can set up rules to automatically notify you (or others) via email, Slack, etc., when specific important
events occur in your Talos account.
Example: You could create a rule to send an email to an administrator if a "Site is set to Test Mode," or if a
"Device is Deleted." This helps key people stay informed about significant changes.
To create a rule, you give it a name, choose the log category you want to monitor (e.g., changes to Sites,
changes to Devices), the specific operation (e.g., "Update," "Delete"), and any conditions (e.g., only if the
field "test mode" was updated). Then you define who gets notified and how.
Company Logs:
Found under Company > Logs.
This log shows important changes that happen at the tenant or company account level itself, rather than
site-specific events.
Examples: New user invitations being accepted, updates to global contacts.
Audit Logs:
Found under Company > Audit Logs.
This provides a more detailed trail of what happened in the system and who made changes. It tracks
things like user logins, logouts, and specific configuration changes made by users.
This is very useful for security audits and for understanding who changed what, and when.
Rollback Feature: A key feature of Audit Logs is that for some types of changes (like if a workflow was
accidentally deleted or modified incorrectly), you can often find the previous versions in the audit log and
"rollback" or restore the older version.
Restore: 
5. Autofeed Toggle (on Alarms Page)
This is a feature on the Alarms page that helps with automatically assigning alarms to operators.
How it Works: An operator (or an administrator for specific roles) can enable "Autofeed" and set up conditions.
When an alarm comes into the buffer that matches those conditions, Talos will automatically assign that alarm to
the operator who has autofeed enabled with those matching criteria.
Example Conditions:
"If Alarm Type is FIRE, assign to me."
"If alarm Severity is higher than 5, assign to my group."
"If alarm comes from Site Group 'VIP North', assign to me."
This helps distribute alarms automatically based on operator specialty, workload, or alarm priority.
Autofeed settings can sometimes be forced on or off for certain user types in the Company > Settings > Users
> User Types area.
Working with Autofeed
In evalink talos, Autofeed is a feature that allows users to automatically assign alarms from the Alarm Queue to
themselves.
In the Alarm Processing Priority, Autofeed is placed after automated workflows and Alarm Dispatcher, but prior to manual
workflows.
As a feature Autofeed is personalized, meaning that you can only enable or disable it for yourself as an operator and
select one of the pre-configured Autofeed filters. Company Admins can add and edit Autofeed Filters.
Enable / Disable Autofeed
You can enable or disable Aurofeed for yourself only.
1. Navigate to Alarms
2. In the Workflows view of the Alarms page, enable or disable the Autofeed Toggle
Company Settings Continued & Key Concepts
In the last section, we started looking at the Company menu. Let's explore a few more important settings and concepts
that are managed at this level.
1. Integrations: Connecting Talos to Other Systems
Under Company > Integrations, you'll find a list of available connections to other alarm panels, third-party tools, and
communication services.
Purpose: Integrations allow Talos to receive alarms from various hardware (like specific alarm panels) or to use
other services (like Twilio for making calls or sending SMS).
Virtual Receivers: Since Talos is cloud-based, many of these integrations work as "virtual receivers." You don't
need a physical receiver box; the connection point is in the cloud. A common example is the Virtual SIA DC-09
Receiver, which allows Talos to receive alarms from panels that use the standard DC-09 protocol.
Enabling Integrations: Most integrations are enabled globally for your company account. For example, to use
the Virtual DC-09 Receiver, you'd find it in the list and make sure it's enabled. Some integrations might require
specific configuration, like entering API keys or account details (e.g., for Twilio, you need to input your SID, token,
and purchased phone number).
Specific Integrations Mentioned:
NXGEN Genesis: For video capabilities.
Virtual SIA DC-09 Receiver: For connecting many standard alarm panels. You might also configure Ajax
panel details here if using DC-09.
Twilio (SMS Receiver, Voice over IP): For sending SMS notifications or making automated/manual calls
from workflows.
Email Receiver/Integration: Can be used to turn incoming emails into alarms or to send email
notifications from workflows.
Webhooks: A powerful technical option that allows almost any internet-enabled system that can send a
web request (a URL call) to communicate with Talos. This can be used for smart home devices, custom
systems, etc.
CALYPSA (Video Analytics): Talos can integrate with CALYPSA. Typically, your cameras send
images/streams to CALYPSA for AI analysis, and CALYPSA can then send verified alarm events to Talos
via webhooks.
When an integration is correctly configured and enabled, it will usually show a green checkmark or "enabled" status.
These enabled integrations then become available to use when setting up new site connections or building workflows.
The integrations fall into the following major groups:
integrations that feed data to evalink talos
Some examples are:
alarm transmitter integrations – a group of integrations that enable receiving alarms from hardware
transmitter devices (alarm panels)
integrations that convert incoming messages arriving by various channels into alarms – for
example, Virtual Email Receiver perform the conversion for email messages, Virtual SMS Receiver – for
SMS
integrations that receive alarms from third-party alarm management systems – for example, the
Alarm.com integration
integrations that connect evalink talos to video surveillance systems and allow receiving real-time video
feeds and the associated alarms / events – for example, the Eagle Eye Networks, NXGEN Genesis
integrations
incoming Webhooks – an integration that makes it possible for external systems to trigger alarms in
evalink talos without any special configuration setup
integrations that enable the user to perform certain actions, for example, from a workflow
Some examples are:
integrations that allow reaching out to a contact person via the specified communication channel
Twilio integrations
Twilio SMS Notifications for sending SMS to a phone number
Twilio Automated Calls for automated calls with text-to-speech capabilities
Twilio VoIP Calls for browser-based incoming and outgoing VoIP calls
Email, Slack integrations – allow sending notifications via email or Slack messenger, accordingly
integrations that allows performing an action on a remote site – for example, the Brivo integration that allows
opening / closing a door
2. Understanding Levels: Global, Organizational Units, Site Groups, and Sites
Talos allows you to organize your customers and their locations in a hierarchy. This is important for applying settings,
workflows, and reports in a structured way. The levels generally are:
Global (Company Level): Settings, contacts, or workflows defined here can apply to everyone unless
overridden at a lower level.
Organizational Unit (Optional): A way to group major customers or large divisions. For example, a national
supermarket chain could be an Organizational Unit.
Site Group (Optional): A sub-group under an Organizational Unit or directly under Global. Using the
supermarket example, all stores in a specific region (e.g., "North Holland") could be a Site Group.
Site: The lowest level, representing the individual customer location or alarm-generating entity (e.g., a specific
store, a panic button).
How it works (Priority):
When Talos looks for a setting, a contact to call in a workflow, or a schedule to apply, it usually starts at the lowest level
(Site) and works its way up.
Example: If a workflow needs to contact "the guard," Talos first checks if a contact with the "Guard" role is
defined specifically for that Site.
If yes, it uses that site-specific guard.
If no, it checks if the Site belongs to a Site Group, and if that Site Group has a "Guard" defined.
If still no, it checks the Organizational Unit (if any).
Finally, it checks the Global (Company) level contacts. This means you can have general global
contacts/schedules/workflows but override them with more specific ones at lower levels if needed.
3. More on Workflows: Manual vs. Automated & Key Concepts
We introduced workflows as scenarios for handling alarms. Let's clarify a few more points.
Manual vs. Automated Workflows:
Manual Workflows: Designed for human operators. An operator picks up an alarm, and the workflow
guides them through a series of steps (e.g., "Call customer," "Check video," "Dispatch guard"). The
operator makes decisions and inputs information.
Automated Workflows: The system handles these automatically without direct human interaction for
each step. Examples: 
An automated call to a customer if their system fails to arm on schedule.
Automatically sending an SMS to a technician if a device reports a technical fault.
Automatically closing very low-priority, known nuisance alarms after logging them.
Often, a process might start with an automated workflow, and if it can't resolve the issue, it then passes
the alarm to a manual workflow for an operator to handle.
Triggers (Incoming Alarm Step):
Every workflow starts with an "Incoming Alarm" step. This defines the conditions under which this specific
workflow should be activated.
You set criteria here, like: 
Alarm Code: e.g., "PA" (Panic Alarm), "BA" (Burglary Alarm).
Alarm Type/Category: e.g., "Panic," "Burglary," "Fire," "Connection."
Schedule: e.g., "Only if this alarm occurs during 'Opening Hours' schedule."
Day of Week: e.g., "Only on Saturday or Sunday."
Logic - "All of" vs. "One of":
Conditions added in the top part of the trigger ("When all of") use AND logic. All those conditions
must be true for the workflow to start. (Example: Alarm code is BA AND Day of Week is Saturday).
Conditions added in the bottom part ("When one of") use OR logic. If any of those conditions are
true, the workflow can start. (Example: Alarm Type is Burglary OR Alarm Type is Fire OR Alarm
Code is PA).
Be careful setting these up! If you put conflicting conditions in the "All of" section (e.g., "Alarm Type is
Burglary" AND "Alarm Type is Fire"), that workflow will never run because an alarm can't be both at the
same time.
Workflow Steps: Once triggered, a workflow proceeds through a series of steps you define. Some common
steps include:
Decisions: Yes/No questions for operators, or automated checks (e.g., "Is site armed?").
Actions: Call someone (manual or automated via Twilio), send an SMS, send an email, update a site
status, deploy a guard (via integration).
Wait: Pause the workflow for a set time.
Jump: Go to another step in the workflow.
Close Workflow: End the process, usually with an outcome status (e.g., "False Alarm," "Real Alarm -
Dispatched").
Example: Automating a "Failed to Close" Alarm
A common automated workflow addresses a site that's supposed to arm (close) at, say, 9 PM according to its schedule,
but it doesn't.
1. Trigger: Schedule indicates site should be armed, but status is still "Disarmed."
2. Automated Action: Talos makes an automated call to the site manager: "Your system at [Site Name] was due to
arm at 9 PM but is still disarmed. Press 1 to postpone arming for one hour. Press 2 to notify the monitoring
center."
3. Conditional Steps:
If manager presses 1: Workflow waits an hour. If still not armed, it might call again or escalate.
If manager presses 2 (or doesn't answer after a few tries): The alarm is sent to the operator queue for a
manual follow-up. This saves operators from manually calling every site that forgets to arm.
Adding New Connections: Virtual Receivers
When you need to connect a new alarm panel or device from a customer's site so it can send signals into Talos, you do
this by setting up a "Virtual Receiver" for that site. Remember, since Talos is cloud-based, you're not dealing with
physical hardware receivers in your office; these are all configured in the software.
Where to Add Virtual Receivers:
You typically manage virtual receivers at the individual Site level.
1. Go to the "Sites" page.
2. Find and click on the specific site you want to configure. This will open the site's detail page.
3. Look for a tab or section called "Receivers" or "Virtual Devices".
Adding a New Receiver:
Once you're in the Receivers section for a site:
1. You'll usually see a list of any existing receivers for that site and an "Add" button (often a '+' symbol) to create a
new one.
2. When you click "Add," you'll need to select the type of receiver you're adding (e.g., "Virtual SIA DC-09
Receiver," "Fibro Receiver," or another specific panel type if listed). The options available depend on the
integrations enabled for your company account (as discussed in the "Integrations" section under Company
settings).
3. Depending on the receiver type, different configuration fields will appear.
Common Configuration Settings for a Receiver:
While the exact fields vary, here are some common things you'll configure:
SLA (Service Level Agreement): This determines how often Talos checks the connection to this panel (the
polling interval) and how long it waits before reporting a communication failure. You can often choose from
predefined SLAs (like "SP2 Ethernet 24 hours" which might be a standard single path polling over Ethernet) or
sometimes create custom ones (as seen in Company > Settings > Receivers > SLAs).
Account Number: For many protocols like SIA DC-09, you'll either let Talos generate a unique account number
for this connection, or you might need to enter a specific account number that is programmed into the customer's
alarm panel.
Encryption Key: If the communication protocol supports encryption (like some DC-09 setups), Talos can
generate an encryption key, or you can enter a key that matches the one programmed into the panel. This
ensures the alarm signals are sent securely.
Alarm Definition: This tells Talos how to interpret the alarm codes coming from this specific panel (e.g., "Contact
ID Standard," "SIA Standard," or a custom definition if the panel uses non-standard codes). In most cases,
leaving this as "Default" is fine, as Talos can usually figure out the protocol.
Optional Information: You can often add a device name (e.g., "Kitchen Panel," "Ground Floor PIRs"), hardware
type, or other notes for your reference.
Once you've filled in the necessary details, you click "Submit" or "Save." The new virtual receiver is created for that site.
What the Installer Needs:
After you create the virtual receiver in Talos, the system will provide the key information that the installer needs to
program into the customer's alarm panel on-site. This typically includes:
The IP Address(es) and Port(s) of the Talos virtual receiver that the panel should send signals to. (Everyone
using your Talos tenant will generally use the same set of Talos receiver IPs/Ports).
The Account Number (the DC-09 account you configured).
The Encryption Key (if you enabled and configured encryption).
The installer programs these details into the panel. Once the panel starts communicating, the virtual receiver in Talos
should show an "alive" or "connected" status.
Managing Existing Receivers for a Site:
From the Receivers list for a site, you can usually:
View Status: See if each connection is "alive" (green) or has an issue.
Disable/Enable: Temporarily disable a receiver if you need to stop signals from that panel (e.g., during extended
site maintenance). Re-enable it to start accepting signals again.
Edit: Modify some of the settings (though critical identifiers like Account Number might not be editable; you might
need to delete and re-add if those were wrong).
Delete: Remove a receiver if the panel is decommissioned.
View Logs: For troubleshooting, you can often view the raw "Receiver Logs" for a specific connection. This
shows the exact data packets Talos is receiving (or not receiving) from the panel, which can be very helpful for
technical staff to diagnose communication problems.
Creating and managing these virtual receiver connections correctly is key to ensuring alarms from your customers' sites
reach Talos reliably.
More Company Settings and Key Talos Concepts
We've looked at some general company settings. Now, let's explore a few more areas and concepts that are important
for managing your Evalink Talos environment effectively. Many of these settings allow for deeper customization and
control over how alarms are processed and how your team interacts with the system.
1. Managing Workflows at Different Levels
As we've discussed, workflows are the scenarios or sets of steps for handling alarms. It's important to know that
workflows can exist at different levels in your Talos hierarchy (Global, Organizational Unit, Site Group, Site).
How it Works (Recap): When an alarm comes in for a specific site, Talos looks for a matching workflow. It starts
by looking for a workflow defined directly at that Site level.
If it finds a matching workflow there, it uses it.
If not, it looks at the Site Group the site belongs to (if any).
If still no match, it looks at the Organizational Unit (if any).
Finally, it will look for a Global (Company Level) workflow that matches the alarm criteria.
Default Workflow: You can set one workflow at each level as a "default." If an alarm comes in and no other
specific workflow matches its criteria at that level or any lower level, the default workflow for that level will be
used. This ensures that every alarm has some defined way of being handled.
2. Site Details Page: A Closer Look
When you open a specific site (by clicking on it from the "Sites" list), you get a detailed view with several tabs and
sections.
Overview Tab (Main View):
Site Name & ID: The unique name and system ID for the site. The full URL in your browser when viewing
a site is often a good thing to copy if you need to ask for support about a specific site, as it contains unique
identifiers.
Address & Map: If the address is correctly entered, you can often click a link to see the location on
Google Maps or OpenStreetMaps.
Service/Installer Companies: Any linked service or installer companies for this site are shown here.
Status Overview: You'll see the current statuses for the site (e.g., Active/Inactive, Test Mode, Connection
Status, Arm/Disarm status). Clicking the main "Statuses" button might show a more detailed historical
graph or breakdown. 
Green icons typically mean "healthy" or "normal."
Yellow might mean "partially healthy" or "needs attention."
Red usually indicates an "unhealthy" status or a problem (e.g., disconnected, alarm rule violated).
Insights: A quick look at the site's activity over the last billing period, showing when it was active.
Recent Events/Open Alarms: A list of the latest alarms for this site, and any alarms that are still open and
being worked on. You can often click these for more details.
Open Workflows: If an operator is currently handling an alarm for this site using a workflow, it will be
listed here.
Instructions (General & Specific): If a default workflow for the site has notes, they appear as "General
Instructions." If a specific workflow is active, its instructions are shown. This provides operators with
guidance.
Other Tabs on the Site Page:
Event Logs & Events: Just like the main Event Logs and Events pages, but filtered to show only the
history for this specific site.
Workflows: Lists all workflows specifically linked or configured for this site.
Contacts: Manage contacts and contact lists specific to this site (e.g., keyholders, local emergency
contacts).
Schedules: View and manage arm/disarm schedules or other operational schedules specifically for this
site.
Receivers (Virtual Devices): We covered this – where you add and manage the alarm panel connections
for this site.
Zones: You can define physical or logical zones within a site (e.g., "Zone 1 - Main Floor," "Zone 2 -
Entrance"). Alarms can then be associated with these zones. You can even link zones to specific receivers
if a site has multiple alarm panels. Schedules can sometimes be applied to zones.
Partitions: Similar to zones, often used for larger sites to divide the alarm system into independent areas
that can be armed/disarmed separately.
Criteria Mappings: This is a more advanced feature. It allows you to "translate" incoming alarm signals.
For example, if a very old panel sends a generic "Technical Alarm Zone 1" signal, but you know Zone 1 on
that panel is actually a "Burglary Sensor - Front Door," you can create a mapping here to translate
"Technical Alarm Zone 1" into the more specific "Burglary - Front Door" within Talos.
Alarm Supervision: Useful for devices that don't have a constant "heartbeat" or polling connection (like
standard alarm panels). You can set up a supervision rule: if Talos doesn't receive an expected "check-in"
signal from such a device within a certain time (e.g., "Fridge OK signal" every 2 hours), it can automatically
raise a "Timeout Alarm" (e.g., "Fridge Communication Failure"). This can be used for things like monitoring
guard check-ins too – if a guard doesn't scan a QR code (which triggers a webhook to Talos) every hour,
an alarm is raised.
Test Modes: Configure and manage test modes for this specific site.
More on Alarm Details & Headers (Recap & Expansion)
When you look at the details of an alarm (on the Events page or when it's in a workflow), remember the "headers"
provide a lot of useful context.
Severity: Indicates how important the alarm is. This can often be customized globally for different alarm
categories.
Category: The general type of alarm (Connection, Burglary, Fire, etc.).
Channel: Can route alarms to specific operator groups (e.g., by language, skill).
X-IP: The IP address the alarm signal came from (e.g., the public IP of the customer's panel).
X-Receiver: Which Talos virtual receiver processed this alarm (useful if a site has multiple connections).
X-Tags: Any tags assigned to the site (e.g., "VIP_Customer," "Video_Verified_Site") will show up here, giving
operators instant context.
Important Settings in the Profile Menu (Top Right Icon)
When you click your profile icon in the top right of the Talos interface:
Settings:
Volumes: Adjust sound notification volumes.
Notifications: Control if you get a small pop-up for new alarms.
Language: Change the interface language.
Dark Mode: Switch to a dark theme, which can be easier on the eyes, especially during night shifts.
What's New: (As mentioned before) See recent platform updates.
Help: Access documentation or support resources.
Profile (Your Account Details):
Latest Sessions: You can see a list of where and when your account has been logged in from. This is
useful for security. If you see a login you don't recognize, you can Invalidate Sessions (which logs your
account out from everywhere) and then change your password.
Leave Company: Be careful with this one! It removes your account from the current company tenant.
Creating New Connections: Setting Up Virtual Receivers
A core task you'll perform, especially when onboarding new customers or new alarm panels, is setting up the
"connection" in Talos. This is done by creating what Talos calls a "Virtual Receiver" at the specific site level. This virtual
receiver is the endpoint in the Talos cloud that the customer's physical alarm panel will send its signals to.
Where to Add Virtual Receivers:
1. First, navigate to the "Sites" page from the main menu.
2. Find and click on the specific customer Site where you want to add this new connection. This will open that site's
detailed configuration page.
3. On the site's page, look for a tab or section labeled "Receivers" (it might also be called "Virtual Devices" in some
views or older documentation). Click on this tab.
Steps to Add a New Virtual Receiver:
Once you are in the "Receivers" section for the selected site:
1. You'll usually see a list of any receivers already configured for this site. There will be an "Add" button (often a '+'
icon) to create a new one. Click it.
2. Select Receiver Type: A window or dropdown will appear asking you to choose the type of virtual receiver you
want to create. This list depends on the integrations enabled for your company account. For many standard
alarm panels, you'll select something like "Virtual SIA DC-09 Receiver" (as DC-09 is a common alarm
transmission protocol). Other options might include "Fibro Receiver" or types specific to other integrated panel
brands.
3. Configure Receiver Settings: After selecting the type, you'll get a form with several fields. Here are the common
ones, especially for a DC-09 type receiver:
SLA (Service Level Agreement): This setting tells Talos how often to expect a "check-in" or "poll" signal
from this panel to know it's still online, and how long to wait before declaring a communication failure if
those signals stop. 
You can often choose from predefined SLAs, like "SP2 Ethernet 24 hours" (meaning a single path
Ethernet connection polled according to a 24-hour standard).
Sometimes you can create custom SLAs with specific polling and reporting times (this is usually
done in Company > Settings > Receivers > SLAs). For most DCO9 connections, a standard SLA
will be suitable.
Account Number (DC-09 Account): This is a critical piece of information. 
You can either let Talos automatically generate a unique account number for this new connection.
Or, if the alarm panel is already programmed with a specific account number (e.g., it's being
migrated from an old system), you can often enter that existing account number here. The key is
that the account number in Talos must match the account number programmed into the panel.
Encryption Key: If the panel and protocol support encryption for alarm signals (which is good for
security), you can enable encryption. Talos can generate a secure key, or you can input a specific key.
This key must also be programmed into the alarm panel to match.
Alarm Definition: This tells Talos how to understand the specific alarm codes coming from this panel. For
most standard panels, leaving this as "Default" or selecting "Contact ID Standard" or "SIA Standard" is
usually correct. Talos is pretty good at figuring out the common alarm formats. You'd only choose a more
specific or custom definition if you know the panel uses very unusual codes.
Optional Information: You can usually give the receiver a descriptive name (e.g., "Main Panel - Ground
Floor," "Backup GSM Communicator") and add other notes for your reference within Talos.
4. Save: Once all the necessary fields are filled in, click "Submit" or "Save."
Information for the Installer:
Once you save the new virtual receiver in Talos, the system will provide you with the crucial details that the on-site
installer needs to program into the customer's physical alarm panel. This usually includes:
The IP Address(es) and Port(s) that the panel must send its signals to. These are the addresses of the Talos
cloud servers.
The Account Number that you configured in Talos.
The Encryption Key, if you enabled encryption.
The installer programs these into the panel. When the panel is powered on and connected, it should start sending
signals (like polls or actual alarms) to the Talos virtual receiver you created. You should then see its status change to
"alive" or "connected" in Talos.
Managing Existing Site Receivers:
From the "Receivers" tab on a site's detail page, you can:
View Status: Quickly see if the connection is online (often shown with a green icon or "alive" status) or if there
are issues.
Disable/Enable: You can temporarily disable a receiver. If you do this, Talos will stop accepting signals from that
panel. This is useful during extensive maintenance at the site. Remember to re-enable it when work is done.
Edit: You can modify some settings of an existing receiver. However, critical identifiers like the Account Number
might not be editable once set (you might need to delete the receiver and create a new one if the account
number was wrong).
Delete: If a panel is permanently removed from a site, you can delete its virtual receiver from Talos.
View Receiver Logs: This is very important for troubleshooting. If a panel isn't communicating correctly, you can
view the "Receiver Logs" for that specific connection. These logs show the raw data packets that Talos is (or isn't)
receiving from the panel. This low-level information can help technical staff diagnose if the panel is sending data
at all, if the data is corrupted, if account numbers don't match, etc.
A Note on "Pools" (Advanced Concept):
Sometimes, for very large setups or to avoid account number collisions if many customers happen to use the same
common account numbers on their panels, Talos might use different "pools" of receiver IPs and ports. This is usually
handled by Evalink support and isn't something you'd typically configure yourself, but you might see slightly different
receiver IP/Port details if a site is assigned to a specific pool.
    
